{
  "doc_id": "55963",
  "text": "The phenomenon of cell tethering has been capturing the interest of researchers for more than a decade. Recently, using quantitative dynamic footprinting, we were able to take topographic-like pictures of a tether occupied cellsubstrate contact zone where tethers in live neutrophils are seen [CITATION_1] . Those images, as well as tether pulling experiments [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] , show the complexity of the tether formation process. Originally [CITATION_15] [CITATION_16] [CITATION_17] , tethers were thought to represent two very different types of tether material with the transition from one material to the other occurring at some time. Here we show that for a fixed set of parameters and a given pulling method, the tether extraction is a deterministic process. The primary reason for that is the fact that in a constant force pulling process the extension rate after crossover is deterministically defined by the dynamic equilibrium formula (Eq. 2). This indicates that the variability in tether pulling experimental data is a result of variability in cell/tether parameter values within the same cell type.",
